Some facts about the popularity and size of R:

  • R is #7 of all programming languages (IEEE Spectrum, 2021)

The other top languages (C, Java, Python and C++…) are all general-purpose languages, suitable for just about any programming task. R by contrast is a language specifically for data science, and its high ranking here reflects the critical importance of data science as a discipline today. In recent years, Python has surpassed R as the most used language in data science, however, it is down to the bandwagon effect! :) - Esben, 2021

  • There are now 18278 ! ! ! available packages on CRAN (CRAN: Contributed Packages, 2021-10-06)

How to use RStudio

  • Create new project
  • Panels and menus
    • rmarkdown for reports, presentations, manuscripts, whatever…
    • R script for functions, shiny ui.R files…
  • Code highlighting/autocompletion
  • Help and cheatsheets
  • Packages, install/load
  • Useful shortcuts (alt + shift + k)

My most used packages:

  • When you load the tidyverse the following suite of packages will be available:
    • ggplot2 for visualizing data.
    • dplyr for manipulating data.
    • tidyr for tidying data.
    • stingr for working with strings.
    • forcats for working with factors/categorical data.
    • purrr for functional programming, tools for working with functions and vectors.
    • readr for reading and writing .csv files (and more).
    • tibble enhanced data frames.

These are all super duper great packages. Start every R project with library(tidyverse)!

  • More great tidyverse packages include:

    • lubridate for working with date/times.

    • hms for time-of-day values.

    • readxl for reading .xls and .xlsx files.

    • haven for SAS, SPSS, and Stata files (Traberg, hvis du vil hive gamle STATA datasæt over i R).

    • dbplyr allows you to use remote databases by converting dplyr code into SQL. Or simply write SQL directly in rmarkdown as sql chunks.

    • glue combine data and strings.

    • tidymodels The tidymodels framework is a collection of packages for modeling and machine learning using tidyverse principles. incredible powerfull suite of packages for machine learning. Deep learning with keras and tensorflow is also supported but are less mature (the Rstudio team is on it). Let me know if you wanna know more…

  • Outside of tidyverse:
    • janitor for quick cleaning of data.
    • here for operating with relative paths. A must if you wanna share your project folder.
    • skimr for quick and comprehensive summary statistics.
    • ggplot2 extensions make even more beautiful plots!
    • patchwork my prefered package for combining plots.
    • beepr to play notification sounds. Helpful when performing time consuming tasks.

Introduction to dplyr

We’ll use the iris dataset provided in base R. Check library(help = "datasets") for many more base R datasets.

iris <-
  iris %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  clean_names()

Dplyr aims to provide a function for each basic verb of data manipulation:

  • filter()
  • arrange()
  • count()
  • select()
  • distinct()
  • mutate() (and transmute())
  • group_by
  • summarise()
  • slice_sample()
  • and more…
iris %>%
  filter(sepal_length < 4.5)
# A tibble: 4 x 5

A quick comparison between the syntax of pandas and dplyr

Pandas is python’s equivalent of dplyr, e.i. the preferred package for data wrangling.

Summary stats

Calculate the total population per continent in 2007 and sort the results in descending order.

gapminder[gapminder['year'] == 2007].groupby(by='continent').sum()['pop'].sort_values(ascending=False)
continent
Asia        3811953827
Africa       929539692
Americas     898871184
Europe       586098529
Oceania       24549947
Name: pop, dtype: int64
gapminder %>%
  filter(year == 2007) %>%
  group_by(continent) %>%
  summarize(total_pop = sum(pop)) %>%
  arrange(desc(total_pop))
# A tibble: 5 x 2
  continent  total_pop
  <fct>          <dbl>
1 Asia      3811953827
2 Africa     929539692
3 Americas   898871184
4 Europe     586098529
5 Oceania     24549947

Creating derived variables

Print top ten countries in the 90th percentile with regards to GDP per capita in 2007.

gapminder_2007 = gapminder[gapminder['year'] == 2007]
gapminder_2007['percentile'] = gapminder_2007['gdpPercap'].rank(pct=True)

Both python and R are great languages for data science, however, the tidyverse syntax seems to be cleaner and easier to read.

The chapter on data wrangling in the r4ds book is a great way to get to know data wrangling in R.

Elegant visualization with ggplot2

mtcars is another dataset provided in base R.

mtcars <-
  mtcars %>%
  rownames_to_column(var = "model")

p <-
  mtcars %>%
  ggplot(aes(hp, mpg)) +
  geom_point()

p

Adding layers

p + geom_label_repel(aes(label = model))

mtcars %>%
  ggplot(aes(hp, mpg)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  labs(
    title = "Hej Traberg",
    subtitle = "hvad så der?",
    color = "automatic?"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(labels = c("yes", "no"))

iris2 <-
  iris %>%
  mutate(hej = sepal_length + 100)

Many plots combined with patchwork

p5 + p6

p1 | (p2 / p3 / p4 + plot_layout(guides = "collect")) +
  theme_solarized(light = FALSE)
